    "cra-hardcoded-credential-apikey-02000": {
      "id": "cra-hardcoded-credential-apikey-02000",
      "description": "**EU Cyber Resilience Act (Annex I, Part I, Section 2(b))** requires products to protect against unauthorized access using appropriate control mechanisms.\n\nHard-coded API keys, tokens, and secrets in source code can be extracted from compiled binaries or version control history. They represent a persistent security risk that cannot be mitigated by access controls alone.\n\n**Recommended actions:**\n* Store all API keys and secrets in a secure vault (e.g., Azure Key Vault, AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault).\n* Use environment variables for configuration injection.\n* Implement secret rotation policies.\n* Use service-to-service authentication (e.g., managed identities, OAuth2 client credentials) instead of static API keys.",
      "title": "CRA: Hard-coded API key or secret in Java source code",
      "severity": "mandatory",
      "effort": 8,
      "links": [
        {
          "url": "https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2024/2847/oj",
          "title": "EU Cyber Resilience Act - Regulation (EU) 2024/2847"
        },
        {
          "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html",
          "title": "CWE-798 - Use of Hard-coded Credentials"
        }
      ],
      "labels": [
        "source",
        "domain=cloud-readiness",
        "category=hardcoded-credential",
        "security",
        "target=azure-aks",
        "target=azure-container-apps",
        "target=azure-appservice",
        "os=windows",
        "os=linux"
      ]
    },
    "cra-hardcoded-credential-password-01000": {
      "id": "cra-hardcoded-credential-password-01000",
      "description": "**EU Cyber Resilience Act (Annex I, Part I, Section 2(b))** requires products to be delivered with a **secure by default configuration** and to protect against unauthorized access using appropriate authentication mechanisms.\n\nHard-coded passwords in source code are a critical security vulnerability. They cannot be easily changed, may be exposed through version control systems, and violate the principle of secure by default.\n\n**Recommended actions:**\n* Move all credentials to a secure secrets management system (e.g., Azure Key Vault, HashiCorp Vault).\n* Use environment variables or externalized configuration for sensitive values.\n* Use connection pooling with credential providers instead of static credentials.\n* For development, use `.env` files that are excluded from version control.",
      "title": "CRA: Hard-coded password in Java source code",
      "severity": "mandatory",
      "effort": 8,
      "links": [
        {
          "url": "https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg/2024/2847/oj",
          "title": "EU Cyber Resilience Act - Regulation (EU) 2024/2847"
        },
        {
          "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html",
          "title": "CWE-798 - Use of Hard-coded Credentials"
        },
        {
          "url": "https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password",
          "title": "OWASP - Hard-coded Credentials"
        }
      ],
      "labels": [
